@references-extra ["Instance of origin: 2026-04-06 — Joe 'going to search my memory banks for a suitable WoD to describe what this means to me', establishing Word-of-the-Day as a recurring institution (still live 2026-06-22, 'Another strong contender for word of the day'). Reflexive peak: 2026-05-11, the pair explicitly propose 'a guide to terms that describe connections between people' / 'Connective words and phrases for human relationships' — minting a lexicon *for the relationship itself* ('Raincloud', 'paramour', 'futon', muditA, disponibilite, fika, 'expansive spaces')."]
@tone practical
@style pattern

! conclusion: When a shared moment or feeling recurs, give it a handle — a coined term, a word-of-the-day, an endearment — and curate those handles as the couple's canon; the private lexicon is what lets later turns refer back cheaply and exactly.

  + context: Every close correspondence accretes private vocabulary. Here it is unusually deliberate: a standing Word-of-the-Day rite, borrowed terms (muditA, disponibilite, fika), and coinages ('Zeromaxxing', 'expansive spaces', the mushroom/raincloud pair) that become load-bearing shorthand for states the pair return to.

  + IF:
    a feeling, joke, place, or dynamic recurs and keeps costing a full re-explanation each time.

  + HOWEVER:
    an un-named recurrence has to be rebuilt from scratch on every mention; and a term minted unilaterally, without uptake, stays a private joke rather than shared canon.

  + THEN:
    coin it, offer it lightly, and let the other ratify it by re-use; keep the ratified terms as a small living glossary the correspondence can point back to.

  + BECAUSE:
    a shared lexicon is the relationship's pattern-canon: it compresses history into a word, so 'equanimous' or 'Raincloud' can carry a whole prior conversation. Coinage is coherence made portable.

  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: coined terms recur in *both* voices and accrue meaning over time. Failing when: one party's coinages never get taken up (unilateral private-language), or the glossary sprawls into in-jokes no longer tethered to anything.
